Okay, I'm terrible at this posting thing, because I already tried this once and it didn't work and ate my whole, really long response. So you're just going to have to trust me when I say that it was really good. Doc Spatz, I don't expect you to trust me because I'm the very incarnation of evil feminazi multiculturalism that's destroying your beloved Fatherland, but hey, a girl's gotta do what a girl's gotta do.<br><br>
Some brief recaps of my now non-existent response:<br><br>
I was born in Saigon in June 1974. My family (my parents and I) were evacuated in April 1975. Though I remember nothing about Vietnam, my entire life has been about Vietnam. I originally wanted to start this thread to make some kind of gesture toward the veterans who fought in the war, because I've known very few vets (or very few who've chosen to make it known to me) and it seemed to me that if I was going to process all this, this part of my life, I needed to at least give it a shot. Thankfully, some very wonderful people responded and it's been very exciting for me; I feel like I'm on the verge of a relevation, so that's been something very, in my vernacular, effing cool. I'm not sure what's up with this site, but I'm very glad it was here for the time it was so that I could do this.<br><br>
Betty: There is a book called &quot;Tangled Memories: The Vietnam War, The AIDS Epidemic, and the Politics of Remembering&quot; by a Marita Sturken which discusses reactions to Maya Lin's memorial design, the subsequent furor over additional memorials and how one memorialized war, protrayals of vets in popular culture, and the role of the &quot;Vietnam Syndrome&quot; in the rhetoric of the Persian Gulf War. I've hardly even capped the tip of the iceberg in my own work, but I'll be discussing in my PHD work the twenty-year commemoration of the refugee camps at Pendleton, San Diego, Kim Phuc at Veterans Day in DC, Little Saigon, and more. It's gonna be a number of years yet before I finish!<br><br>
It's late here, so I'm going to bed. Thanks all for responding, I really appreciate it and the chance it gave me to do some coalition-building. <br>
 
